WHY ArrayList: 
- Maintaining Insertion Order
- Unknown Size
- Fast Access by Index
- Adding / removing at the end


methods: 
- basic = add, remove, set, get, clear, size, contains, sort, isEmpty
- addAll, retainAll, removeAll, containsAll


ways to define the ArrayList : 

//good practice
List<String> test = new ArrayList<>();

ArrayList<String> test = new ArrayList<>();
ArrayList<String> test = new ArrayList<String>();
ArrayList<String> test = new ArrayList<>(Arrays.asList("Apple", "Banana", "Orange"));

//using java 8 
ArrayList<String> list7 = Stream.of("Foo", "Bar", "Baz").collect(Collectors.toCollection(ArrayList::new));


snipets :

		ArrayList<String> test = new ArrayList<>();
		test.add("A");
		test.add("B");
		test.add("C");
		test.add("D");
		
		System.out.println("printing the list : " + test);

		System.out.println("iterating the list : ");
		for(int i=0; i<test.size(); i++) {
		System.out.println(test.get(i));	
		}
		
		test.set(0, "Z");
		System.out.println("updated list  : " + test);
		
		String query = "d";
		
		System.out.println("finding a match in the ArrayList : " + query);
		if(test.contains(query)){
			System.out.println("match found");
		}else {
			System.out.println("no match found");
		}
		
		// adding two arrayLists 
		ArrayList<String> test2 = new ArrayList<>(Arrays.asList("U", "V", "W", "X"));
		test.addAll(test2);
		System.out.println("combined list : " + test);
		
		// retaining any element
		List<String> test3 = new ArrayList<>(Arrays.asList("L", "E", "O", "T", "A"));
		//test.retainAll(test3);
		//System.out.println(test);
		
		// remove all 
		//test.removeAll(test);
		//System.out.println(test);
		
		if(test.containsAll(test3)) {
			System.out.println("match found");
		}else {
			System.out.println("no match found ");
		}


o/p:

printing the list : [A, B, C, D]
iterating the list : 
A
B
C
D
updated list  : [Z, B, C, D]
finding a match in the ArrayList : d
no match found
combined list : [Z, B, C, D, U, V, W, X]
no match found 